title: Minimalistic filament spool holder small footprint 4 OneUp / Printrbot etc.

description.text:
This filament spool holder has a diameter of 43mm and a max. footprint of 60x60mm. It can be used with an extra ball bearing. I took one from a bicyle. It is very small and easy to slice, print or modify.
In case you need more grip use double sided adhesive tape underneath. Then there is also an adapter with a diameter of 48mm to 43mm. The 48mm was found using Sainsmart filament spools. The thing is very uselful for spools like the one from Sainsmart, that have very bad spools (like cardboard) and do not work too well in the spool holders where the spool is stored vertically.
So with one or more adapters you can build a rotating tower.
The baseplate has only 60x60mm so this filament sppol holder should be printable even on very small printers like mine here (OneUp Model1) or teh Printrbot. Maybe I add more adapters and variations over time. Enjoy.

description.header: Clean you vinyl LPs and device screens with this Ghostly Vinyl Cleaner.
description.text:
This is the easiest to make record and screen cleaner. It is an original work by me. Now 2 sizes, 4.4" (110mm) long and 2.75" (70mm) long
Simply print the model, and add a microfibre or velvet cloth. To use, put your record on the turntable and while it is rotating, hold the cleaner so that it gently touches the record. A tiny amount of anti static can be applied to the cleaner before use. Works well as a iPad, phone and screen cleaner.

Print at whatever resolution you like without supports.  The pictured print is at 300micron layer height.     If the object is not laying horizontal in the slicer, rotate it.  
To insert the microfibre cloth, fold the cloth so that it is about the length of the recess, roll the cloth around a sponge or something soft and push into the cleaner.  Ridges on the walls should keep the cloth in place.    
If you are using anti static liquid or spray, apply the anti static to the cleaner before wiping the record.    
Enjoy clean records

remixed_from.author: doctek
remixed_from.title: Hypocycloid How To Part 2 - Some Experiments

description.text:
The title of this Thing should be "Hypocycloidal - Schmidt - Moineau Paste Extruder", but that's a bit too long!
This design uses the Hypocycloidal Drive from these two Things: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:79231 and http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:81879, couples with a modified version of the Scmidt Coupling here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:233667 and builds on the design of the Moineau Extruder here: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:15538. The result is an extruder design driven with a NEMA14 stepper ready to mount on your X-carriage and try out.
See it in action here: http://youtu.be/KyuY_WrrCKw
TODO: Now that I have a working design, I need to try putting various materials through it. I have pumped yogurt just fine, but need to try more viscous (stiffer) materials.
Here it is pumping Peanut Butter: http://youtu.be/4vtTN_aZ8iU
One problem to be solved is the leakage of material into the coupling chamber.
 Still a problem, but not over-doing the supply pressure helps. Another challenge is just how to deliver the material to the inlet.
** Needs a better method, but the tube part is OK.
Did I mention that this is a Work in Progress?
Please try it out and contribute the results of your experiments!

See my earlier Hypocycloid things for building the drive. Use a 5 lobe lower case, a 5 lobe output, and a rotor with 5 lobes on the lower section and 4 lobes on the upper section. That will give you a 4 to 1 gear ratio and is what I've used so far. It's easy to get a higher ratio if needed.
While most of the design is done in OpenSCAD, the arms for the Schmidt coupling were designed using FreeCAD simply because it was so easy. My re-design of the original does two things: 1) the plastic fiber pivots are replaced by 2-56 screws, washers, and nuts. 2) the upper and lower coupling disks are modified for my purposes.
There are two versions of the Coupling Cover. One has windows in it so you can see the coupling in operation (it's amazing) and one that has no windows for safer operation during printing. Pick your favorite.
The profiles for the Moineau chambers were created using a Python script I wrote. It is available if anyone would like to have it for creating custom profiles for pumps having fewer or more lobes.
Since this is a Work in Progress, expect to see some updates as I experiment.

Please note, however, that the rotor center still moves eccentrically. That is why the Schmidt coupling is required. I did several experiments trying to drive the rotor with a shaft to the center. I could not make that work. The eccentric movement must be accommodated.
comments.author: doctek

comments.text: great job btw Doctek
comments.author: unfold

comments.text: The double helix (2:3) version reduces more (largely theoretical) pulsation vs the single helix (1:2) version; increase volume pumped per revolution (can be disadvantage as you'll need more reduction on the stepper). Another benefit is that instead of the sidewise movement of the rotorhead, the rotorhead makes a circular movement. I was using a direct axle coupling with 1:2 rotor and because of the sidewise movement the distance between the motor axis and rotorhead was less when the rotorhead was in the middle of the stator vs on the extremes resulting in a bit of wobble. With the circular movement of the 2:3 that distance would always be the same.
comments.author: unfold

comments.text: Thanks for your interest in the Moineau Extruder! Great question that I wish I had a better answer for. The main reason I am using the 2 lobe/3 lobe design is that the 2 lobe impeller is thicker and stronger than the single lobe impeller. I tried the single lobe and was very concerned that it would break under load. The two lobe impeller is more than twice as thick. My guess is that the 2 lobe impeller also pumps more smoothly having two chambers for continuous material delivery. However, I have not worked through the theory to prove this, so I could be wrong. I'm even less sure about how the volume of material pumped per revolution compares between the two designs. It's an interesting question I hope to have time to address someday.

This is my design for the 2014 Thingiverse Make-A-Thon and it won me first place! It prints with no supports within a 50mm^3 space. Once assembled, you simply rotate the nautilus shell to the desired angle and set your phone in, resting its back on the shell, keeping captive with the lip at the front.

Prints great at .2mm layer heigh, standard speeds and feeds. This was printed on 5th gen makerbot machines in PLA, and worked well at layer heights of .3mm as well.
Once printed, remove the two retaining pins from the bottom of the base. They should come out with little effort, but this may be adjusted in the future. Take the Nautilus shell, and place it horizontally in the base. Insert the pins carefully on either side of the indented surfaces in the center of the shell piece. they only go in one way, and should friction fit. the pins are in place when the tabs on the end of the pins fall into the cutouts on the rear of the base. Finally, crack loose the front 'jaw' on the print to allow your phone to have a nice rest on the beach.

Fits 1 (one) Maxbotix LV-EZ(x) in a Hollow flexible mount Brick with a 2 Segment extension tube. This mount is intended to basically hold up a MaxSonar LV-EZ0 Range Finder Sonar for prototyping some ideas. The base mount brick itself is equal to 3 (2x4) Lego bricks that can be "bricked" into a nice support structure to hold it in place. Then the end mount that holds the sensor can be positioned in any direction. The wires from the end mount are then able to be threaded through the tube and through the base Brick. It should be compatible with All "EZ" series. This Kit Includes:

  • FlexSegBase2 - Ultrasonic Base Mount Brick with Flex Mount Tube Nib.

  • (2) FlexSeg_WN2 - Flex Tube Segments.

  • FlexSeg_MountBak2 - Flex Segment Mount Back Clip and Tube Nib.

  • FlexSeg_MountFace - Front Mount Brick that Clips to Mount Back and holds the Sensor.
    • Actually this is "2" things.. You can just print the bbFlexSeg_WN2 if you just want a flexible tube..

• Print parts Face Down.

  • Print as many Flex Segments as you want.

  • In MakerWare, I modify the "Medium" settings:
    Quality: Layer Height = 0.16
    • All other defaults are the same. If you don't have a 3D printer we can make you one pretty cheap.. badbrick.com/catalog Notes: To reduce splitting Flex Segments when assembling the tube we suggest you lightly sand the small top nub and the inside of the bottom nub. However, don't sand too much as it will reduce the tubes static positioning. Note++: We do split them all the time, mainly because we can't seem to listen to our own advice and sand the nubs. However, because we print them vertically they still retain enough friction to keep position on light loads. Little dab of super glue will fix the split right up.. Serious about the sanding though.. It helps.

This camera case fits a Sony Effio-V board camera. The front and back are designed to be press-fitted and held with small squares of 3M mounting tape for quick assembly/dis-assembly while keeping the structure fairly lightweight. A hinge allows the user to tilt the camera up or down.
The design was inspired by this PZ0420 camera case: http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:159726
Suggestions for improvement are welcomed. Enjoy!

Bill of materials:
Printed case parts
M3 screw (1)
M3 locknut (1)
Small 5x5mm squares of 3M mounting tape (4)
Instructions:
Print the parts and test fit the camera in the front part of the case. I suggest printing at 200 micron layer height or finer. If there is a little bit of side-to-side play, that's fine. Cut 4 small pieces (around 5x5mm) of 3M mounting tape, and place them on the legs of the back part of the case. With the camera installed, press fit the back of the case into the front. The mounting tape should hold the assembly together snugly. if there is any jiggle, disassemble and add small amounts of mounting tape where appropriate to snug the fit (I didn't need to do this).
The holes are designed for a M3 bolt (25-30mm long or so) and a M3 locknut. You may need to use a 3mm drill bit to clean out the holes prior to installing the bolt.
Notes:
  • The fit of all parts are quite snug, so a well-calibrated printer is a must.
  • Be careful not to over-tighten the screw and lock nuts, as it will cause the base tabs to crack.
    • Suggestions are welcomed. Enjoy!

description.text:
VERSION 2 NOW AVAILABLE! My K8200 printing Ninjaflex at 50mm/s :
http://youtu.be/SHU8OtSdZwc I reworked the inner filament guide block for better printing with flexible filaments. Works for PLA,ABS and other filaments too.
The part includes a connector for E3D hotends with direct coupling.
Just print it out, slide your hotend in and fix it with the clamp.
The part has very close tolerances!
Print with 0.2 mm layer height max and at least 30% infill.
I included the 123D Design files as well, in case you want to change something. Comments and suggestions for improvements are welcome. After some test prints i updated the part to get better results.
I moved the filament guide hole 0.5mm towards the hobbed bolt and added a conic entrance for the filament to reduce drag. I also added a plug on filament guide to keep the filament straight in the middle of the extruder.

After some test prints i updated the part to get better results.
I moved the Filament guide hole 0.5mm towards the hobbed bolt and added a conic entrance for the filament to reduce drag. I also added a removble "plug on" Filament guide to keep the filament straight in the middle of the extruder. The part has very close tolerances!
Print with 0.2 mm layer height max and at least 30% infill.
I found out 100% infill will give less warping of the part while cooling.
Material can be ABS but PLA is sufficent, cause the mount of the hotend won't get hot during operation. Print the main part laying sideways with the opening of the hotend mount facing up.
Drill the filament guide hole to at least 3.2mm, i suggest 3.5.
Drilling is necessary to get correct diameter and smooth walls. The first mount of the Extruder may need some force.
put it in as far as it goes and then tighten it up evenly with the screws. That should make it slide well into place. If the Filament guide won't snap on easily just heat it up with a lighter and then mount it.

After cutting you have 3 pieces of wood and two pieces of plastic.
Attach the two pieces of plastic in the slots of the middle wood section. Glue them together in such
a way that the front is in line. Now glue the bottom woodpiece to the contraption. Finally glue the
top/front piece to the construction en let it all dry.
I advise a 10 to 20 Watts fluorescent lightbulb, please do not use a classic lightbulb due to the heat

The worst areas are going to be the horizontal strokes in the A and the E, obviously... we'll have to print one out and see if I made the letters too salient.

Got inspiration from all the different 3D printed prosthetic hands and was thinking my conductive and flexible PI-ETPU 95-250 Carbon Black filament could add a dimension or 2... This dualstrusion will create the finished finger with joints and a force sensitive fingertip. The fingertip has a outer shell that, when pressed, will connect to the inner conductive surface, thus creating a closed circuit. This model is only a quick proof of principle design... and the picture of a full hand is only a visualization of a hand that could be printed in one go... perhaps!? Are you up for the challenge?
The smudging of the conductive material resulted in a closed loop at aprox 8.5k and when pressing the tip it goes down to 7.2k
Its my first dualstrusion, I used 0.7mm nozzles and I could for sure need to adjust the height of the nozzles and it would be great to have retractable nozzles to get rid of the smudging... I designed the finger in a straight shape but it would be better to print it bent outwards, the TPU material has a problem to bend the finger all the way back after it has been closed lots of times... or change the shape of the joints... 3D printed with ABS and PI-ETPU 95-250 Carbon Black filament.
PI-ETPU 95-250 Carbon Black is a professional 3D printer UV-stable, flexible and conductive filament. Don´t need the conductivity? description.text: This robot hand features internal ligaments that torsionally link successive sections of the fingers to allow the efficient use of a single tension element - i.e. you only need one tendon per three jointed finger. Reducing the finger to a single degree of freedom greatly improves its ability to firmly grasp cylindrical objects.

View the video instructions here: https://youtu.be/CfB8Mrh1dSI Simply press in 6x10x3mm bearings (available from Technobots website, part no: 4255-130) between the finger sections and add the torsional ligaments by threading nylon fishing line (100daN approx. diameter 1.1mm) through the finger sections to link the top of one joint to the bottom of the section two along i.e. the top of the knuckle is linked to the underside of the middle section and the top of the first section is linked to the bottom of the tip section and vice versa. Attach dyneema tendons by spreading the ends of a dyneema kiteline and embedding the fibres in polymorph. A single spring made from 3mm polyurethane tubing is attached to the top of the knuckle to extend the fingers.
